<HEAD>Athletics 5, Giants 0 in Series Game 1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BEN WALKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Baseball Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Oakland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Athletics </ORGANIZATION>, showing the pitching and power that made them baseball's winningest team, dismissed the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Giants </ORGANIZATION> 5-0 Saturday night in the World Series opener. <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> pitched a five-hitter for his third postseason victory this year. He walked one and struck out six. <ORGANIZATION> Oakland </ORGANIZATION> roughed up National League earned run average leader <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Garrelts </PERSON> for five runs in four innings. <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> and <PERSON> Walt </PERSON> <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON> each homered and the <ORGANIZATION> Athletics </ORGANIZATION> finished with 11 hits, including three by <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> McGwire </PERSON>. <PERSON> Rickey </PERSON> <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON>, the most valuable player in the American League playoffs, went 2-for-5 with a run-scoring single but did not steal a base after swiping a record eight in the playoffs. <PERSON> Will </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>, the National League playoff MVP, went 2-for-4. <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON>, throwing 95 mph fastballs at twilight, had trouble only on balls hit back to him. <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> made a two-base throwing error on <PERSON> Robby </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>'s comebacker in the first inning In the third, <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Uribe </PERSON> got an infield hit when <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> failed to cleanly catch the ball and threw a shade late to first base. <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON> walked on five pitches to start the second and one-out singles by <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinbach </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> made it 1-0. With runners at first and third, <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON> nubbed a slow grounder to first that <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> fielded, double-pumped and threw home to <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>. <PERSON> Steinbach </PERSON>, however, kicked the ball loose from his rival catcher's mitt for an error and was safe. <PERSON> Rickey </PERSON> <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON> singled home another run for a 3-0 lead. <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> homered to open the third and <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON> homered to lead off the fourth.
