<HEAD>Thurderstorms, Wind Rip Upstate New York, Kill 1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS CAROLA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Violent thunderstorms ripped across upstate <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Saturday with heavy rain, hail and wind up to 85 mph, knocking out power to thousands of homes and killing at least one person. A man was killed and three other people, including two boys, were slightly injured when their mobile home was blown several hundred feet from its foundation in McDonough, police said. A <ORGANIZATION> Canfield </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, man escaped injury when a gust of wind blew his single-engine <ORGANIZATION> Cessna </ORGANIZATION> aircraft onto its side as he was preparing for takeoff from <LOCATION> Niagara </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, police said. A sky diver who was aloft when the storm hit was yanked upward 1,500 feet in three seconds, said <LOCATION> Niagara </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Sheriff's Deputy <PERSON> Duane </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacobs </PERSON>. The parachutist, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Konstabel </PERSON>, 32, of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Seneca </LOCATION>, told police that when he hit the ground, he was dragged 300 feet across a barbed-wire fence and into some trees in the town of <LOCATION> Newfane </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Konstabel </PERSON> was reported in stable condition with injuries to his right leg in <ORGANIZATION> Erie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Buffalo </LOCATION>. After <PERSON> Konstabel </PERSON> began ascending he cut his main parachute away and descended using his reserve chute, said <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Szczepanski </PERSON>, sky-diving instructor for <PERSON> Konstabel </PERSON>'s group. `` This thing just came across the lake and whacked us,'' <PERSON> Szczepanski </PERSON> said of the storm. Thousands of homes were left without electricity when