<BYLINE>By BRAD CAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SILVERTON, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Declaring that he has an `` unfinished agenda,'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatfield </PERSON> said Saturday night that he would run for a fifth term. The announcement by the <ORGANIZATION> Oregon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> ended months of speculation about the plans of the state's most popular politician. `` I've come to the conclusion that ours is an unfinished agenda,'' <PERSON> Hatfield </PERSON> said told about 350 supporters. <PERSON> Hatfield </PERSON> said he played a key role in fashioning the recent congressional compromise on harvest of old growth timber. Environmentalists had initally opposed harvesting any virgin timber on federal land; the compromise allows some logging. `` I will not rest until we have secured a long-term solution to our timber supply problems,'' <PERSON> Hatfield </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Hatfield </PERSON>, 67, also said that if re-elected he would work to provide better health care to Oregonians, to step up the fight against drugs, and to slow the nuclear arms race. Following a long-standing tradition, <PERSON> Hatfield </PERSON> made the announcement in <LOCATION> Silverton </LOCATION>, where he's launched all of his previous campaigns. Friends and political supporters of <PERSON> Hatfield </PERSON>, including President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, had encouraged the senator to run again. Gov. <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldschmidt </PERSON>, a Democrat, also asked him to run again. <PERSON> Hatfield </PERSON> won a seat in the <ORGANIZATION> Oregon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> in 1950 and was elected secretary of state in 1956. After two terms as governor, he was elected to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> in 1966. A formal Naval officer who was one of the first Americans to witness firsthand the aftermath of the atomic bombing of <LOCATION> Hiroshima </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Hatfield </PERSON> earned a reputation as a staunch foe of the <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> war.
