 Most of the 6,500 residents forced to flee when a frozen pizza plant leaked deadly ammonia gas were allowed back into their homes early Sunday, but people with breathing problems were told to wait. Authorities ordered a complete evacuation of the town Saturday night when the gas, used for refrigeration, began leaking and spread quickly over an area of about half a mile, said Fire Department Lt. <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Winters </PERSON>. Twenty-four people affected by the gas were taken to hospitals and four were admitted, officials said. Many others were given oxygen by paramedics who rushed to the scene from around the largely rural southeastern quarter of <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. The anhydrous ammonia leak at the <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Jeno </PERSON>'s plant was brought under control by 10:55 p.m., said Mayor <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Carey </PERSON> Assistant Fire Chief <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Long </PERSON> said people started returning to their homes just after 5 a.m. Sunday. `` The fog is still heavy. It's starting to lift up a little and it smells kind of funny. You get a little odor of it,'' <PERSON> Long </PERSON> said. The mayor warned that the elderly, people with breathing problems and small children could be affected by remaining vapor and should remain away from the town until the ammonia dissipated completely. Police had ordered people to evacuate a seven-block area near the plant, then expanded the order to cover the entire town as the gas spread, said Highway Patrol Dispatcher <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Riley </PERSON>. Sheriff's deputies went door-to-door ordering people out of their homes. Resident <PERSON> Vicki </PERSON> <PERSON> Dailey </PERSON> said she, her husband and two children fled choking fumes about 9 p.m. `` We were out in the driveway and at first could not smell anything,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Dailey </PERSON> said. `` But within about two minutes, we started smelling it and decided to get out. We were choking.'' Repair crews working breathing bottled oxygen reported the leak came from a ruptured 16-inch pipe, but the cause of the break was n't known, said <LOCATION> Vinton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Deputy Sheriff <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>. Anhydrous ammonia fumes can be fatal if inhaled, according to an emergency guidebook by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION>. Calls to the plant were not answered Sunday morning.
