<TEXT>
 Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> said Sunday that technological advancements such as television are threatening traditional family life on this <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> island nation. `` Modern life has reached the shores of the island. Asphalt roads and electricity arrive the same time as the means of social communication'' such as television and videos, the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> told a stadium full of Roman Catholics on the tiny island of <LOCATION> Rodrigues </LOCATION>, 390 miles east of the main island of <LOCATION> Mauritius </LOCATION>. `` In itself, this is praiseworthy progress, but, as in other societies, <PERSON> Rodrigues </PERSON> suffers in full from influences such as those of the video that threaten stability in the family,'' the pontiff said. The 36,500 French-speaking inhabitants of <PERSON> Rodrigues </PERSON> are mainly African-descended farmers and farm workers. About 97 percent are <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION>. The pope expressed concern about the growing number of islanders leaving to seek jobs in the booming economy on the main island, where he arrived Saturday after eight days in <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>. He returns to <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> on Monday. `` For a long time, <PERSON> Rodrigues </PERSON> seemed to be living tranquilly as one big united family in which everyone knew everyone else and no one was an outcast,'' said the pope. `` And suddenly, there is worry about the future.'' He urged the islanders to safeguard traditional values in a country where tourism has doubled in the past six years to about 200,000 annually. Cardinal <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Margeot </PERSON> has warned that the influx of outsiders is creating serious `` moral'' problems for Mauritians. As the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> toured the island, topless European and South African women sunned themselves on beaches in a land where most native women wear long dresses and do n't smoke or drink alcohol. In the past six years, 90,000 jobs have been created on <LOCATION> Mauritius </LOCATION>, a democracy where people of several races and religions coexist peacefully. The government of Prime Minister <PERSON> Anerood </PERSON> <PERSON> Jugnauth </PERSON> has actively courted foreign investment, creating a special export zone to diversify the economy from its centuries of dependence on sugarcane. But Mauritians have become concerned about pollution as factory smoke begins to cloud the sharp-edged mountains around the lagoons and gas stations appear alongside the palm trees. The government last year created a department to monitor the quality of life and financed it from liquor and cigarette taxes. <LOCATION> Mauritius </LOCATION> also has become a transit point for drug smugglers. Signs at the international airport warn of a death penalty for trafficking in narcotics.
