<HEAD>Group Saves Old Mural of B-17</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 While World War II still raged, an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> serviceman had a burst of inspiration and painted a giant picture of the famed B-17 bomber on a brick wall at a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airfield. The B-17 is ancient aviation history now, and the airfield is used as a drag-racing strip. The name of the fatigue-clad artist is barely remembered. But the mural that stood in obscurity since 1944 has been taken down as part of a plan to restore it and move it to a permanent place of honor. `` It was a thrill to see something that has been in the dark for more than 40 years come into the light again and be saved for posterity,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nimmo </PERSON>, one of a group of English enthusiasts who seek to perserve such relics. The picture _ which shows the famous `` Flying Fortress'' unloading its bombs while anti-aircraft shells burst around it _ was taken down Saturday from its place at <LOCATION> Podington </LOCATION> airfield, an old base of the World War II-era <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> 8th <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Podington </LOCATION> airfield, 65 miles north of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, was one of about 130 8th <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> bases for bombers and fighters in the eastern <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> flatlands. They were established to raid <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and German-occupied territory. After the war, most of the <LOCATION> Podington </LOCATION> field reverted to farming. The brick huts used by the crews have remained as workshops for drag-racing on the airfield runway, and the control tower has been converted into a house. The mural was on a piece of wall on farmland. The removal team had to get permission from the farmer to take down the painting, and they will have to rebuild the wall. A benefactor has given them 750 red bricks for the task. With help from the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> air base at <LOCATION> Alconbury </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> Cambridge </LOCATION>, the mural is to soon be transported to <LOCATION> Duxford </LOCATION>, another old <ORGANIZATION> 8th </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> field about 35 miles east of <LOCATION> Podington </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Imperial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> War </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> maintains <LOCATION> Duxford </LOCATION> for its collection of historic aircraft and will set up the B-17 mural as part of its display about the <ORGANIZATION> 8th </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>. The 12-by-8 foot painting was done in about 1944 by a staff sergeant named <PERSON> Walderschmidt </PERSON>, <PERSON> Nimmo </PERSON> said. `` We think he was on the ground crew,'' he said. `` We do n't know anything else about him except that we heard he is still alive in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. We do n't know his first name or where he lives.''
