<HEAD>Alessandra Marc Makes Debut in `Aida'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 12th graf pvs, `The rest ...' to CORRECT Radames to hero
sted heroine.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE SILVERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Just a few years ago, opera audiences and critics were bemoaning the lack of any new <PERSON> Verdi </PERSON> sopranos to fill the void left by the retirement of Leontyne Price. Then came a young American upstart named <PERSON> Aprile </PERSON> <PERSON> Millo </PERSON>. On Saturday came another _ <PERSON> Alessandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Marc </PERSON>. Even in a Metropolitan Opera season notable for exciting debuts, <PERSON> Marc </PERSON>'s first performance as `` Aida'' was something special, as the standing-room-only crowd acknowledged with its repeated ovations. Here is the genuine article _ a dramatic soprano with an opulent voice that can be thrilling in its power or tender in its warmth as the occasion demands. She has the gleaming tones to ride above the full forces of orchestra and chorus that <PERSON> Verdi </PERSON> assembled for the Triumphal Scene of Act 2. She has the artistry to create a portrayal of the tormented Ethiopian princess in the aria `` O patria mia,'' which opens the Nile Scene in Act 3. She also has a few problems. Vocally, the lower register of her voice is undeveloped and colorless. At the other end of her range, she has trouble reining in the volume and seems unable to float the high pianissimos that are one of <PERSON> Millo </PERSON>'s trademarks. Dramatically, <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> is hampered by being enormously overweight, a condition that makes believable involvement with the other characters difficult. In one of the opera's most moving scenes, her father, <PERSON> Amonasro </PERSON>, is supposed to throw Aida to the ground in angry rejection. The most that baritone <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Pons </PERSON> could do was push her gently and allow her to slump on a nearby rock. <PERSON> Marc </PERSON>, who is in her early 30s, grew up in the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, area, as <PERSON> Judith </PERSON> <PERSON> Borden </PERSON>. She changed her name a few years ago, saying she was tired of being confused with the soprano <PERSON> Judith </PERSON> <PERSON> Blegen </PERSON> and wanted a name with a good international ring to it. She has the name. Now it's up to her whether she will have the career to match. The rest of Saturday's `` Aida'' was workmanlike but undistinguished. As the wooden hero, Radames, tenor <PERSON> Nicola </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinucci </PERSON> strained at his high notes; mezzo <PERSON> Stefania </PERSON> <PERSON> Toczyska </PERSON> was earnest, if not thrilling, as the villainous Amneris, and <PERSON> Pons </PERSON> brought warmth and intensity to the brief role of <LOCATION> Amonasro </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Christian </PERSON> <PERSON> Badea </PERSON>'s conducting was lively and sensitive. <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> is the second American singer to make a triumphant debut this season at the Met, a company often criticized for being too slow to engage promising native talent. Two weeks ago, tenor <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Leech </PERSON> sang <PERSON> Rodolfo </PERSON> in <PERSON> Puccini </PERSON>'s `` La Boheme'' to great acclaim. <PERSON> Millo </PERSON>, who has been singing major roles at the Met for several years, got to open the current season as `` Aida.'' There's more to come. The coloratura June <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> will debut in <PERSON> Verdi </PERSON>'s `` Rigoletto'' later this fall; <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunn </PERSON>, another contender in the <LOCATION> Verdi </LOCATION> sweepstakes, sings in `` Il Trovatore'' in February, and soprano <PERSON> Ashley </PERSON> <PERSON> Putnam </PERSON> will sing in Gounod's `` Faust'' in March.
