<FIRST>r i AM-SouthAfrica-Profiles     10-15 0972</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa-Profiles,1006</SECOND>
<HEAD>Profiles of Eight Freed Political Prisoners</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-South Africa, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are profiles of the eight South African political prisoners freed Sunday. Five were tried and sentenced in 1964, along with <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>, to life in prison for sabotage and conspiracy in a trial in the <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> suburb of <LOCATION> Rivonia </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> WALTER </PERSON> <PERSON> SISULU </PERSON>: <PERSON> Sisulu </PERSON> ran day-to-day operations of the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> as secretary-general from 1949-54, when the government ordered him to resign. He was one of the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION>'s most important leaders in the years when it grew from a small organization into a mass movement. He helped organize a national campaign to defy apartheid laws in 1952. Born May 18, 1912, in the Xhosa homeland of <LOCATION> Transkei </LOCATION>, he joined the congress in 1940 and formed the <ORGANIZATION> Youth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> in 1943 to press for more aggressive tactics. After his acquittal along with 155 other defendants in a 1956-61 treason trial, <PERSON> Sisulu </PERSON> was restricted to his house, arrested six times, and finally convicted of furthering the aims of the now-outlawed guerrilla group. While on bail pending appeal he went underground and was captured three months later in <LOCATION> Rivonia </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> AHMED </PERSON> <PERSON> KATHRADA </PERSON>: <PERSON> Kathrada </PERSON>, arrested at age 17 for participation in a passive resistance campaign in 1946, was a member of the high command of the <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' military wing. He is one of only two Rivonia defendants who denied all the charges against him. He was convicted on only one count, sabotage. <PERSON> Kathrada </PERSON> was born Aug. 21, 1929, in the western <LOCATION> Transvaal </LOCATION> to a scholarly Moslem family and became involved in politics at age 11. He joined the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in the early 1940s and as general secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Transvaal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> was instrumental in linking it to the <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. He was acquitted in the 1956-61 mass treason trial but placed under house arrest in 1962. He went underground a few months before his arrest at <LOCATION> Rivonia </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> ELIAS </PERSON> <PERSON> MOTSOALEDI </PERSON>: As a founder of the <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> regional command of the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION>'s military wing, <PERSON> Motsoaledi </PERSON> hid recruits and helped send them abroad for military training and procuring arms, prosecutors alleged at the <LOCATION> Rivonia </LOCATION> trial He said he joined the military wing in 1962. Born in northern <LOCATION> Transvaal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Province </LOCATION> on July 26, 1924, the son of a migrant laborer, <PERSON> Motsoaledi </PERSON> worked in <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> as a servant and at factories. He joined the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in 1949 and the congress in 1948. In 1949, he became chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Non-European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unions </ORGANIZATION>, organized strikes and was banned in 1952. He was held in solitary confinement for three months in 1960 before going underground. His wife, <PERSON> Caroline </PERSON>, lives in <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION>. Three of their seven children are in exile.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> RAYMOND </PERSON> <PERSON> MHLABA </PERSON>: At the <LOCATION> Rivonia </LOCATION> trial, <PERSON> Mhlaba </PERSON> denied he belonged to the high command of the <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' military wing. But he was identified in the South African press as the man who became commander-in-chief after the arrest in 1962 of <LOCATION> Mandela </LOCATION>. In 1952, <PERSON> Mhlaba </PERSON> was the first congress leader arrested as part of the defiance campaign, when he led blacks through the `` whites only'' entrance to a train station. He was born Dec. 2, 1920, son of a policeman. He dropped out of school, became active in trade unions in <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Elizabeth </LOCATION>, joined the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in 1943 and the congress in 1944. In 1986, prison authorities allowed him to marry the mother of three of his eight children.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> ANDREW </PERSON> <PERSON> MLANGENI </PERSON>: <PERSON> Mlangeni </PERSON> said at the <LOCATION> Rivonia </LOCATION> trial he had agreed to carry messages for the congress' military wing, but he denied he was a member. He was accused during the trial of being responsible for explosives and being a member of the <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> command. Born in <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> on May 30, 1926, he worked as a golf caddy to pay for school and later as a clerk, bus driver and journalist. He joined the congress in 1951 and was regional secretary for the township of <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION> from 1958-60, before he went underground.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> WILTON </PERSON> <PERSON> MKWAYI </PERSON>: <PERSON> Mkwayi </PERSON>, 66, briefly took command of the congress' military wing after the arrest of <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>'s colleagues in 1963. He was arrested shortly afterward and sentenced to life imprisonment in 1964 after being convicted on 58 counts of sabotage. The judge said <PERSON> Mkwayi </PERSON> received guerrilla training in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and had taught African <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> members how to make bombs. In 1987, <PERSON> Mkwayi </PERSON> was allowed to marry his common-law wife, <PERSON> Irene </PERSON>. She died in December.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 JAFTA MASEMULA: <PERSON> Masemula </PERSON>, 58, a member of the outlawed <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Africanist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> guerrilla organization, was sentenced to life in prison in 1963 for sabotage. At the time of his arrest in 1961, he was a primary school teacher in <LOCATION> Atteridgeville </LOCATION>, near <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION>. Some other members of the <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Africanist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> were freed last year after agreeing to a government offer of release in exchange for renunciation of violence. <PERSON> Masemula </PERSON> refused to do so.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
