<HEAD>Darman Says Automatic Budget Cuts Would Be Good Medicine For Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The White House budget chief said Sunday it might be best if <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> leaves in place automatic spending cuts that take effect Monday night rather than follow the past practice of rolling them back. The $ 16 billion cut, formally known as a sequestration, is automatic under the 1985 Gramm-Rudman Act that was designed to force the president and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to reduce the federal deficit. This year, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the administration failed to find a compromise. `` I think it may be that sequester is the best available alternative. At least it is real,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Darman </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> and Budget. The automatic budget cuts of Gramm-Rudman took effect in 1986 and 1987 as well, but <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> acted quickly to restore the lost funds, a process that <PERSON> Darman </PERSON> called `` phony.'' `` This time, if it goes into effect, I think it would be good if people would live with it and say, ` do n't restore the cuts,''' <PERSON> Darman </PERSON> said on the <ORGANIZATION> ABC-TV </ORGANIZATION> program, `` This Week With <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Brinkley </PERSON>.'' The chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, Rep. <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Panetta </PERSON>, D-Calif., said he thought <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> could agree on a formula similar to a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> package passed last Friday that met the Gramm-Rudman targets The failure to meet those targets, said <PERSON> Panetta </PERSON>, was linked to the sharp drop in stock prices Friday. `` I thi