<HEAD>Town Evacuated and Four Hospitalized After Ammonia Accident</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 11th, `Elderly people...,' to give details
on where evacuees were sent.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WELLSTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An ammonia leak at a pizza plant prompted the all-night evacuation of this entire town of 6,500 people and left four people hospitalized Sunday, authorities said. An evacuation order was lifted shortly after 5:00 a.m. Sunday morning, said <LOCATION> Wellston </LOCATION> Assistant Fire Chief <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Long </PERSON>. `` We had some fog that moved in last night _ it was keeping the ammonia smell around parts of town,'' <PERSON> Long </PERSON> said. `` The sun dried it up.'' Deadly anhydrous ammonia used for refrigeration at the <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Jenno </PERSON>'s plant began leaking about 8 p.m. Saturday when a compressor cap blew off a 16-inch pipe inside the plant, said Mayor <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Carey </PERSON> The evacuation of the town was ordered at 10:30 p.m. and the leak was contained by 11 p.m.. About 50 people were taken to area hospitals Saturday night and early Sunday Most were given oxygen treatments and released, said <LOCATION> Vinton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Deputy Sheriff <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> on Sunday. Dozens of other residents were given oxygen treatment by emergency medical units and paramedics Saturday night. `` They all wanted to know if their lungs were going to blow up,'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. `` They slept everywhere last night, in their cars, they were all over the place.'' <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Dalton </PERSON>, spill unit supervisor of the <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, said <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> and plant officials did not immediately know how much ammonia escaped or how much was in the system. `` Once the plant has made the repairs, then they'll recharge and determine how much they lost,'' <PERSON> Dalton </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Wellston </LOCATION> policeman <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Bates </PERSON>, 26, and <PERSON> Jeno </PERSON>'s employee <PERSON> Evelyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilliland </PERSON>, 39, were in fair condition at <ORGANIZATION> Holtzer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, said a nursing supervisor who did not give her name. <PERSON> Ronnie </PERSON> <PERSON> Russell </PERSON>, 27, and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON>, 36, were also in fair condition at <LOCATION> Oak </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Community </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>, said nursing supervisor <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> McFann </PERSON>. Elderly people and nursing home residents were advised not to return until later Sunday morning to give the cloud time to dissipate completely, <PERSON> Long </PERSON> said. Residents of the town's two nursing homes, <LOCATION> Edgewood </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Manor </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Jenkins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Memorial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, were returned to the homes by about 9 a.m. Sunday, he said. Evacuees were taken by school bus to two schools in the nearby towns of <LOCATION> Hamden </LOCATION> and <PERSON> McArthur </PERSON> and to a community center in <LOCATION> McArthur </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Ethel </PERSON> <PERSON> Gussler </PERSON>, a dispatcher at the <LOCATION> Vinton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> sheriff's department Police and sheriff's deputies said no looting was reported following the evacuation. Employees from <PERSON> Jeno </PERSON>'s sanitation division returned to work early Sunday, <PERSON> Dalton </PERSON> said. The plant manufactures frozen pizzas. Environmental damage from the leak appeared to be minimal, he said. Inspectors had feared that the ammonia would dissolve into water in streams, storm drains and sanitary sewers. <PERSON> Dalton </PERSON> said ammonia can kill fish and the bacteria used at sewage treatment plants to break down raw sewage. Runoff from the plant was contained in a diversion ditch around the plant and did not reach streams, he said. `` Anhydrous ammonia reacts with liquid in your lungs, changes form, then attacks tissues. It can directly suffocate you,'' <PERSON> Dalton </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Wellston </LOCATION> is about 90 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>.
