<HEAD>Hurricane in 1900 Killed More Than 6,000 in Galveston</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Storm Jerry, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Galveston </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, a barrier coast off the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> coast, was struck by the deadliest hurricane on record in September 1900. The powerful storm sent a wall of water washing over the island, and some called it the worst natural disaster in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> history. The death toll from that storm is n't certain, but experts generally agree it easily topped 6,000. Some accounts placed the number of people killed at 8,000. The storm caused damage estimated at $ 30 million and $ 40 million. Fifteen years later, in August, another hurricane hit <LOCATION> Galveston </LOCATION>. The official death toll was estimated at 275, much lower than the great 1900 storm. That's because storm-wary residents had raised the grade of the island and built a seawall to protect them from surging tides blamed for most of the deaths. Still, damage from the 1915 storm was set at $ 50 million.
