<HEAD>Japanese Investors Calm Despite Wall Street Plunge</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Markets, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Japanese investors Monday were visibly calmer about the stock market than they were after Black Monday two years ago. A retail brokerage office of the giant <ORGANIZATION> Nomura </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in the central <LOCATION> Ginza </LOCATION> district was somewhat busier than a usual Monday morning, but the market players seemed to be waiting for bargains rather than unloading their shares in a panic. `` I expect the Nikkei index to remain bearish all day, but I am not so worried because we all know it is due to external factors,'' said an investor watching the key index shortly after the market opening. `` I am going to sit and wait for a while and start buying shares later on as shares start hitting the bottom,'' he said. In October 1987, after a plunge on Wall Street that went down in history as Black Monday, brokerages in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> were packed with massive sell orders that led to the Black Tuesday here. The Nikkei average fell 3,836 points, or about 15 percent, on Oct. 20, 1987, following a 23 percent plunge on Wall Street, largely due to panic selling by private investors. `` Japanese private investors seemed to have learned the lesson that fluctuation of the Wall Street index is only one of many aspects of the <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> market,'' said a dealer at <ORGANIZATION> Nikko </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, speaking on condition of anonymity. `` It is undoubtedly an important elmement, but not necessarily as dominant as it was thought to be.'' <PERSON> Keiishi </PERSON> <PERSON> Nishida </PERSON>, a dealer at the <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> office of <ORGANIZATION> Kidder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peabody </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said: `` This is nothing like the crash two years ago when private investors rushed to the brokers from early in the morning and sold all they had. I do n't think any investors expect <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> shares to drop like <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> this time.'' But he added that investors remained hesitant to place buy orders because `` they want to make sure that the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> plunge was only a one-time thing, and the <PERSON> Dow </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> will not go down further Monday there.'' <PERSON> Nishida </PERSON> also attributed <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>'s moderate recovery in late morning to programmed trading. `` After the sizable drop, buy orders from institutional investors on program-trading came in,'' he said. `` But other than that, I do n't expect much of buy orders today.'' Another investor in the <LOCATION> Ginza </LOCATION> office commented: `` In a trading day like today, you must deal with caution.''
