<SECOND>AM-Markets-Mutual Funds, 1st Ld-Writethru,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>Weekend Redemptions Running `Light' At Nation's Biggest Stock Fund</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT week's decline to 216 points sted 226</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The head of the nation's largest stock mutual fund said redemption requests have been running `` very light'' since Friday's market scare partly because investors are in for the long haul and are n't necessarily spooked by even a large decline. Following last week's 216-point decline in the Dow Jones industrial average, most of which hit during the last hour of trading Friday, some market observers voiced fears that mutual funds would be hit with massive redemptions by clients wanting to get out of the market. That could force fund managers to dump stocks in order to raise enough cash to pay their clients, thereby exacerbating the market turmoil. But money market guru <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON>, who heads <ORGANIZATION> Fidelity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investments </ORGANIZATION>' $ 12.5 billion <ORGANIZATION> Magellan </ORGANIZATION> fund, said Sunday that `` the real fast, aggressive people left before the close on Friday. This weekend -LRB- redemptions have -RRB- been very light.'' <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON> admits that over the past six weeks he has increased <ORGANIZATION> Magellan </ORGANIZATION>'s cash position by $ 350 million to $ 850 million, but it was not because he feared his fund's shareholders would start cashing out. Rather, he said in a telephone interview from his <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> home, `` I have n't been finding that many stocks that are undervalued.'' Investors generally view stock funds as long-term investments and are n't likely to `` rush out and redeem that quickly,'' said <PERSON> Erick </PERSON> <PERSON> Kanter </PERSON>, vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> Investment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, a Washington-based trade association of mutual funds. Stock funds account for roughly 25 percent of total mutual fund assets of $ 242 billion. Most stock funds keep about 10 percent of their total assets in cash. A Gallup survey of 150 <ORGANIZATION> Fidelity </ORGANIZATION> customers late Friday and early Saturday found that 84 percent said they had invested for the long term while 4 percent said they intended to sell their fund shares in the next few weeks. <PERSON> Kanter </PERSON> said that even following Black Monday, Oct. 19, 1987, when the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> plummeted 508 points, only 2 percent of total stock fund assets actually were redeemed. Those who did redeem `` wound up losing a lot because stock funds rebounded very quickly,'' <PERSON> Kanter </PERSON> said. Even <ORGANIZATION> Magellan </ORGANIZATION> posted a gain at the close of 1987, although it was a 1 percent increase rather than the 41 percent gain that the fund had been tracking before Black Monday. Still, <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Magellan </ORGANIZATION> has had `` redemptions up until August. ... The public has been very nervous since'87 and has been cutting back pretty steadily.'' <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON> said he believed the overall stock market likely would have a net gain for the full year, making 1989 the record-setting eighth consecutive advancing year. `` The reason we've had eight straight years is because we had 16 years of nothing,'' he said. `` The market went sideways or down for 16 years.'' The previous longest advance began in 1896 and lasted for six years, <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON> said.
