<HEAD>Tel Aviv Stock Exchange Dives 6.9 Percent</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 1st 2 graphs to CORRECT market not first to open; ADDS
other market notes; uppicks 3rd graf pvs: ``What is ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEL AVIV (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s stock exchange, one of the few foreign markets to trade on the weekend after the Wall Street plunge, witnessed frantic trading and a 6.9 percent drop in share value Sunday, officials said. Although the <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aviv </LOCATION> market is small and limited to local stocks, analysts looked to the exchange for signs of how other world markets would react. Among a handful of small foreign markets to trade over the weekend, <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> lost ground but <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> posted a small gain. `` What is happening here is a reaction to the news coming from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> on Friday,'' said <PERSON> Yossi </PERSON> <PERSON> Nitzani </PERSON>, director of the stock exchange. `` There are large amounts of selling in almost all areas of the market. `` The feeling here is that something very significant happened in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Nitzani </PERSON> said. `` Capital markets do n't like uncertainty, so the first reaction was to get out and wait for things to become clearer.'' Trading was three times its usual volume, with stocks declining in paper value by $ 400 million, <PERSON> Nitzani </PERSON> said in an interview. It was the sharpest fall since October 1987, when Israeli share values were off 8.5 percent in reaction to the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> crash. Sunday's fall in the dollar-linked bond market was less dramatic, down 2 percent. No <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> stocks are traded in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and no Israeli stocks are sold on Wall Street, but the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market has strong influence in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> because the two economies are closely intertwined. The <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aviv </LOCATION> exchange is open from Sunday to Thursday and closed Friday and Saturday for the Jewish sabbath. <PERSON> Simcha </PERSON> <PERSON> Sadan </PERSON>, an economist at <ORGANIZATION> Tel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviv </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, said on <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> there could be a spillover into <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> because of extensive economic ties between <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, its major ally and source of nearly $ 3 billion in annual aid. `` If the American economy gets sick, then we will certainly get pneumonia,'' he said. The director of one of <ORGANIZATION> Tel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviv </ORGANIZATION>'s largest trading houses predicted further drops after <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> openend. `` I am afraid it is not finished,'' he said, speaking on condition of anonymity. `` <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> will probably fall when it opens Monday and that will influence people here as well as in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>.''
