<BYLINE>By SHERI T. PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Vending machines have come a long way from bubble-gum machines and coffee, soda and candy dispensers. Now a machine will sell you hot, personal-size pizzas, or a fresh cup of cappuccino or espresso coffee. These and other innovations _ along with coinless `` debit card'' machines _ were introduced over the weekend at the annual convention of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Automatic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Merchandising </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. The trade show drew thousands of representatives of the $ 20.9 billion vending machine industry, association spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Stone </PERSON> said Sunday. The upscale coffee machines, manufactured by the Italian corporation <PERSON> Borghi </PERSON> SpA, crush a small amount of coffee beans for each cup, blast steam through the grounds, and dispense a strong, tasty brew in a tiny cup. `` We're looking for the upscale, higher-end consumers who appreciate a better, European cup of coffee and ethnic groups who do n't like <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> coffee because they find it too diluted,'' said <PERSON> Erick </PERSON> <PERSON> Feitshans </PERSON>, director of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> operations for <PERSON> Borghi </PERSON>. `` We use a filter ... that de-chlorinates and purifies the water,'' said <PERSON> Feitshans </PERSON>, who noted there is an industry trend toward using filtered water `` so we do n't use dirt water out of city plumbing systems.'' The machines also make hot chocolate and regular, American-style coffee for consumers with more conventional tastes. Coffee costs from 80 cents to $ 1.20, with cappuccino the costliest. <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> businessman G.W. Black and his son, <PERSON> Brett </PERSON>, offered a 7-inch cheese and pepperoni pizza that takes 60 seconds to make in their Pizza Chef, a microwave-pizza oven. They hope the $ 2 tab for a pie will be within the budget of college students looking for a late-night snack. `` It's a little bigger than a pan pizza at Pizza Hut and it's a buck cheaper,'' <PERSON> Black </PERSON> said. `` It's not doughy and it's not super crispy. I think we did a good job ... for a microwave pizza.'' <PERSON> Bert </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Vos </PERSON>, owner of <ORGANIZATION> De </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vos </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, a vending machine company in the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, displayed his `` Deepfrozen'' machine that sells a consumer a frozen dinner and has a built-in microwave oven to heat it up. To make it easier for customers to pay for these items, vendors are moving toward introducing debit card systems, especially on college campuses, <PERSON> Stone </PERSON> said. Customers can feed bills, such as $ 10, into a machine which produces a magnetic-strip credit card. When the card is inserted into a vending machine to buy an item like a 50-cent candy bar, the purchase price is automatically deducted, leaving $ 9.50 on the card. Students at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kentucky </ORGANIZATION> are already using the debit cards for the campus cafeteria, vending machines and even washing machines, said <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON>, customer service manager for <LOCATION> Debitek </LOCATION>, based in <LOCATION> Chattanooga </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, which makes one of the debit card models. `` And it's much easier for the vending industry,'' he said. `` It takes all the coin mechanisms out of the machine,'' which cuts the maintenance costs for collecting money and unjamming slots. `` It -LRB- the technology -RRB- is here already ... but it looks like this is the year it's going to take off,'' <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON> said.
