<HEAD>Japanese Investment Doesn't Threaten America, Experts Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING to CORRECT cycle designator.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE KURTENBACH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Japanese investment in American real estate and businesses does not threaten the national security or economic health of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, experts told a conference in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> last week. But strong public resentment over highly publicized Japanese purchases of American companies, like <ORGANIZATION> Sony </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s recent $ 3.4 billion takeover of <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION>, indicates <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> should do more to reassure Americans of its good intentions, they said. `` Foreign investment is good for both economies ... as President <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> once said, ` a rising tide lifts all the boats,''' said <PERSON> Elliot </PERSON> <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON>, a former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> secretary of both commerce and defense. Aside from helping cover the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade and federal budget deficits, Japanese investment can aid technology transfers and help revitalize <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industries through the sharing by Japanese companies of management and production techniques with American partners, speakers at the conference said. They acknowledged, however, that the perception of Japanese investment among many Americans was strongly negative and could get worse. `` Americans grew up in an era when the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> was the source, not the recipient, of foreign investment. They feel we are losing control of our economic destiny,'' said <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON>, who heads the Washington-based <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investment </ORGANIZATION>, a conference sponsor. The American sponsors and their Japanese counterpart, the Council for Better Corporate Citizenship, said they held the conference to help the Japanese understand why their investments in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> can be controversial even while the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government welcomes them. In a recent Gallup poll reported in <ORGANIZATION> Newsweek </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> magazine </ORGANIZATION>, 52 percent of the people polled said they viewed Japanese economic might as a greater threat than Soviet military power. Japanese investment in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has come under fire largely because of its rapid growth _ twice as fast as that of other nations _ in highly visible areas, <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Armacost </PERSON> told the conference. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s total investment in American real estate, corporations and subsidiaries skyrocketed from $ 4.7 billion in 1980 to $ 53.4 billion in 1988. Of a total $ 65 billion in foreign direct investment in 1988, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> accounted for $ 14.2 billion, just behind <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s $ 21.5 billion. Economists estimate Japanese investment will reach $ 21 billion this year. Highly publicized lawsuits against Japanese firms accusing them of racial and sexual discrimination along with problems in balancing American and Japanese management styles and staff in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> offices have contributed to the backlash against Japanese investment, speakers said. <PERSON> Alice </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, a partner in the New York-based law firm <ORGANIZATION> Milbank </ORGANIZATION>, Tweed, <PERSON> Hadley </PERSON> and <PERSON> McCloy </PERSON>, urged Japanese investors to keep a low profile in making investments _ to `` avoid plastering <ORGANIZATION> ` </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>' all over everything'' _ to seek expert advice to avoid lawsuits over largely avoidable problems, and to hire and promote the best American talent to positions of responsibility <PERSON> Armacost </PERSON> noted that 85 percent of all chief executive officers in Japanese overseas subsidiaries are Japanese, while only 20 percent of the CEO positions in overseas subsidiaries in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> are filled by expatriates. `` Until companies are perceived as creating the best environment for American workers, you wo n't get the best,'' Ms. <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said. Japanese investors can also allay American anxiety over their economic activities by getting more deeply involved in community activities in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, speakers said. `` A Japanese corporation in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> needs to be more responsible to community concerns than it would be at home,'' said <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON>, singling out the <ORGANIZATION> Hitachi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>'s program of matching grants to community projects. While there is substantial room for improvement in the way Japanese firms operate in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, there is no evidence to support charges that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is `` buying <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> on the cheap,'' said <PERSON> Jonathon </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Colby </PERSON>, a partner in <ORGANIZATION> Blackstone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` Japanese companies buy only high-quality assets at a fair price,'' <PERSON> Colby </PERSON> said. Japanese companies operating subsidiaries in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> are reinvesting their profits from American operations rather than sending them home, said <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosenblatt </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investment </ORGANIZATION>. The rate of return from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> affiliates from 1981 to 1988 was only 3.3 percent for Japanese-owned firms, compared with 5.6 percent for all foreign-owned firms in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, indicating that Japanese are investing in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> for the long term, he said. Officials of the <ORGANIZATION> Departments </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> said there were no signs that Japanese investment was threatening <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> national security. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mullen </PERSON>, deputy undersecretary of defense, said that in cases in which a joint venture would involve the sole <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> company with a strategic product or technology, the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> makes arrangements to ensure the deal will not compromise national security.
